# eY OS Design Principles

---

# Philosophy

Design should reduce thinking, not increase it.

The interface exists to help users make decisions quickly.

Every screen should feel calm, focused and intentional.

---

# Principle 1

Purpose before Layout.

Never ask:

"Where should this widget go?"

Always ask:

"What problem does this solve?"

---

# Principle 2

Action over Information.

Information without action creates noise.

Every widget should help the user decide something.

---

# Principle 3

The Five Second Rule.

A user should understand:

• What needs attention.

• What has changed.

• What happens next.

within five seconds of opening Home.

---

# Principle 4

Progressive Disclosure.

Home shows summaries.

Details belong inside modules.

---

# Principle 5

One Responsibility.

Every widget has one responsibility.

Avoid combining unrelated information.

---

# Principle 6

Calm Interface.

Avoid clutter.

Avoid unnecessary colours.

Avoid unnecessary animations.

Whitespace is valuable.

---

# Principle 7

Consistency.

Cards.

Buttons.

Typography.

Spacing.

Icons.

Interaction.

Everything follows one design system.

---

# Principle 8

AI Assists.

AI should:

Summarise.

Recommend.

Prioritise.

Never overwhelm.

---

# Principle 9

Information Hierarchy.

Everything belongs to one of four categories.

ACTION

Tasks

Shopping

Inbox

TIME

Calendar

Travel

Reminders

Quick Status

KNOWLEDGE

Documents

Property

Research

Notes

INTELLIGENCE

AI Brief

News

Recommendations

Insights

---

# Principle 10

Home is Sacred.

The Home page is not another dashboard.

It is the decision centre.

If information does not help answer:

"What should I focus on today?"

it probably does not belong on Home.

---

# Principle 11

Design Once.

Build Once.

Think Twice.

Code Once.

---

# Principle 12

Framework First.

If functionality is reusable:

Build it inside eY Widgets.

If functionality is application specific:

Build it inside eY OS.

---

# Design Goal

Beautiful enough to enjoy.

Simple enough to understand.

Powerful enough to replace dozens of daily apps.
